
TY  - JOUR
T1  - Integrating Transaction Cost and Institutional Theories: Toward a Constrained-Efficiency Framework for Understanding Organizational Design Adoption
AU  - Roberts, Peter W.
AU  - Greenwood, Royston
Y1  - 1997/04/01
PY  - 1997
DA  - 1997/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1997.9707154062
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1997.9707154062
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 346
EP  - 373
VL  - 22
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Transaction cost and institutional theories are integrated in order to enhance understanding of the process by which entities adopt new organizational designs. By grafting cognitive and institutional constraints into the comparative-efficiency framework favored by transaction cost theorists, theorists using the constrained-efficiency framework demonstrate both how efficiency-seeking organizations may be biased in favor of current designs and those that are legitimated within their institutional contexts. The article closes by overlaying the constrained-efficiency framework onto the discussion about the evolution of the M-form of organization, as well as suggesting empirical and simulation strategies consistent with the logic of the constrained-efficiency framework.
AB  - Transaction cost and institutional theories are integrated in order to enhance understanding of the process by which entities adopt new organizational designs. By grafting cognitive and institutional constraints into the comparative-efficiency framework favored by transaction cost theorists, theorists using the constrained-efficiency framework demonstrate both how efficiency-seeking organizations may be biased in favor of current designs and those that are legitimated within their institutional contexts. The article closes by overlaying the constrained-efficiency framework onto the discussion about the evolution of the M-form of organization, as well as suggesting empirical and simulation strategies consistent with the logic of the constrained-efficiency framework.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1997.9707154062
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1997.9707154062
