TY  - JOUR
T1  - Process and Structure in Leader-Member Exchange
AU  - Sparrowe, Raymond T.
AU  - Liden, Robert C.
Y1  - 1997/04/01
PY  - 1997
DA  - 1997/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1997.9707154068
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1997.9707154068
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 522
EP  - 552
VL  - 22
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Theory supporting the key premise of the leader-member exchange (LMX) approach to leadership, that leaders differentiate between subordinates, has not been fully developed. We address this deficiency by (a) returning LMX research to its historical roots in exchange processes by introducing a framework for understanding relationship quality that is based on reciprocity, and (b) extending the traditional domain of LMX research beyond the formal leader-subordinate relationship in order to offer a more complete explanation of the differentiation process. We employ insights derived from social network analysis to describe how social structure facilitates the exchange processes through which leaders assist in incorporating some members into the inner life of an organization but exclude others.
AB  - Theory supporting the key premise of the leader-member exchange (LMX) approach to leadership, that leaders differentiate between subordinates, has not been fully developed. We address this deficiency by (a) returning LMX research to its historical roots in exchange processes by introducing a framework for understanding relationship quality that is based on reciprocity, and (b) extending the traditional domain of LMX research beyond the formal leader-subordinate relationship in order to offer a more complete explanation of the differentiation process. We employ insights derived from social network analysis to describe how social structure facilitates the exchange processes through which leaders assist in incorporating some members into the inner life of an organization but exclude others.
